            </form>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
                        
                        <p>A career in the media industry is so enticing yet so intimidating, for we all know there is no replicable formula to “make it” in media. You need talent, but your talent is not guaranteed to be discovered and appreciated. You often have to go through years of the hope-failure-disheartenment pattern — seven years of it, in McGinn’s case. New York and L.A. are the cradles of thousands of dreams, but perhaps the deathbed of many more.</p>
<p>“You have to give up the money other Duke people are making in other fields and be okay not satisfying the expectations of your parents and other loved ones,” said McGinn, whose Stanford professor father always wanted him to be a lawyer.</p>
<p>But it is better to try and pursue your dream than not trying at all in the first place. McGinn shared his favorite video, <a href="https://vimeo.com/85040589">“The Gap,”</a> which is dedicated to everyone in the creative industry who is is struggling to close the gap between their taste and their work, and helped McGinn during his hardest times.</p>
<p>“When you wanna do something and it doesn’t work out, but you still wanna do it,” McGinn said. “That’s when you know that you actually want it. In the end, it’ll be worth it.”</p>
<!--ceo:replacemode=raw-->




    <figure style="max-width:100%;    " class="embedded-media embedded-image">
        
        <img src="https://snworksceo.imgix.net/dtc/fe454b07-e975-46dc-985d-0952d6cd6105.sized-1000x1000.JPG?w=1000" class="w-100" alt="" />                    <span class="embedded-credit">
                                    <a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/staff/laure-bender">Laure Bender</a>                                            </span>
                    </figure>

